remarks.format:
## Remarks

`SKFourByteTag` encodes four ASCII characters into a single 32-bit unsigned integer, following the OpenType/ISO 15924 convention used throughout font and color-space APIs. Each character occupies one byte, with the first character in the most-significant byte.

Instances can be constructed from four individual characters, from a raw `uint` value, or by parsing a string. Strings shorter than four characters are padded with spaces; strings longer than four characters are truncated. Implicit conversions to and from `uint` are provided for interoperability.

## Examples

```csharp
// Create a tag from four characters
var wdth = new SKFourByteTag('w', 'd', 't', 'h');

// Or parse from a string (padded to 4 chars if shorter)
var wght = SKFourByteTag.Parse("wght");

// Use as a variation axis selector
var coord = new SKFontVariationPositionCoordinate
{
    Axis = wght,
    Value = 700f,
};
```
